<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911217-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>911217-0027.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   World-Wide</HL><DATE>12/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY REVOKED a 1975 &quot;Zionism-is-racism&quot;resolution.   The U.N. vote to rescind condemnation of Zionism, theJewish national movement that led to the birth of Israel in1948, was 111-25, with 13 abstentions. The vote marked onlythe second time in U.N. history that the assembly overturnedone of its own resolutions. The repeal resolution wasspearheaded by the U.S. and co-sponsored by 85 countries.Among them were a number that voted for the originalanti-Zionism draft, including the Soviet Union.</LP><TEXT>   Mideast peace talks in Washington hit new snags as Israelaccused Arabs of &quot;fomenting violence&quot; and Palestinianscondemned an Israeli crackdown in the West Bank and GazaStrip.   ---   BAKER RECEIVED assurances on nuclear arms from Yeltsin andGorbachev.   In meetings with the secretary of state in Moscow, theleaders tried to ease concern about the Soviet arsenal.Russia's Yeltsin vowed that the new commonwealth would imposestrict controls over storage and export of nuclear arms. Healso suggested that eventually only Russia would have nucleararms on its territory. Baker told reporters he felt &quot;veryreassured.&quot; Yeltsin said the commonwealth would beginoperating this month.   Ukrainian President Kravchuk voiced hope that the U.S.would help his republic destroy the nuclear weapons based onits territory &quot;as quickly as possible.&quot;   ---   THE SUPREME COURT AGREED to review a formula forallocating House seats.   The high court said it would -- for the first time --consider the constitutionality of the method used toapportion House seats among states. The court will review a2-1 decision by a federal court that the apportionment lawviolates the constitutional guarantee of equalrepresentation. The lower-court ruling was a victory forMontana, which had filed a suit complaining that it wasunfairly allocated one House seat, rather than two, for the1992 election.   If the justices affirm the Montana decision, other statescould try to send more lawmakers to Washington than thegovernment has allocated to them.   ---   Energy Secretary Watkins announced steps to accelerate theshrinking and consolidation of the nation's weapons-buildingcapacity over the next four years. The planned actions are inresponse to the reduced need for nuclear arms.   ---   The European Community agreed to recognize Yugoslavia'sbreakaway republics as independent states by Jan. 15,Belgium's foreign minister announced. He said the republicswould have to meet certain criteria, however, includingdemocratic rule and human-rights safeguards.   ---   A bomb exploded on a track near Britain's busy ClaphamJunction station in south London, paralyzing the city's railnetwork and disrupting service for as many as one millioncommuters. The morning blast came minutes after a telephonewarning from a man who claimed to be a member of the IrishRepublican Army.   ---   Canada ended its negotiations with the Eskimos by agreeingto split the Northwest Territories in two, giving the Eskimosthe right to hunt, fish and trap across the eastern half. TheEskimos, or Inuit, would receive outright ownership of136,000 square miles of land and compensation totaling morethan $500 million over 14 years.   ---   Duke was dropped from the list of candidates opposing Bushin Georgia's March presidential primary by Republicanofficials who cited &quot;his Nazi past.&quot; The action against theformer Ku Klux Klan leader left Buchanan as Bush's onlyopponent in the March 3 primary. An aide said Duke wouldattempt to get back on the ballot.   ---   Iraq's Saddam Hussein made a major concession toautonomy-seeking Kurds by ruling that members of the Kurdishregional legislature no longer had to swear allegiance to hisBaath party.   ---   Trial proceedings began in Manila for former first ladyImelda Marcos and her son on tax fraud charges, the firsttime any member of the Marcos family has faced prosecution inthe Philippines. The two defendants didn't appear in court.   ---   Salvadoran officials and rebels opened separatediscussions with a U.N. mediator aimed at producing a formalcease-fire and a final agreement for ending El Salvador's12-year-old civil war.   ---   A small radical black group withdrew from negotiationsscheduled to begin Friday between the Pretoria government andSouth African black organizations concerning politicalpower-sharing. The decision by leaders of the Pan AfricanistCongress evoked a standing ovation from 2,000 delegates at aparty conference.   ---   Prime Minister Robinson was defeated in the first generalelections in the two-island republic of Trinidad and Tobagosince a 1990 coup attempt. The winner was the People'sNational Movement, which governed for 30 years before losingin 1986. Robinson's tough austerity measures were widelyblamed for his plunge in popularity.</TEXT></DOC>